  month =	 jul,
  year =	 2001,
  abstract =	 {In this paper we present several weaknesses in the
                  key scheduling algorithm of RC4, and describe their
                  cryptanalytic significance. We identify a large
                  number of weak keys, in which knowledge of a small
                  number of key bits suffices to determine many state
                  and output bits with non-negligible probability. We
                  use these weak keys to construct new distinguishers
                  for RC4, and to mount related key attacks with
                  practical complexities. Finally, we show that RC4 is
                  completely insecure in a common mode of operation
                  which is used in the widely deployed Wired
                  Equivalent Privacy protocol (WEP, which is part of
                  the 802.11 standard), in which a fixed secret key is
                  concatenated with known IV modifiers in order to
                  encrypt different messages. Our new passive
                  ciphertext-only attack on this mode can recover an
                  arbitrarily long key in a negligible amount of time
                  which grows only linearly with its size, both for 24
                  and 128 bit IV modifiers.},
  online =	 {http://www.crypto.com/papers/others/rc4_ksaproc.ps},
