@Article{GolMic84,
	author	= {Shafi Goldwasser and Silvio Micali},
	title	= {Probabilistic Encryption},
	journal	= JCS,
	year	= 1984,
	annote	= {Journal version of \cite{GolMic82}.
                  Seminal paper on security definitions for encryption.
                  Work motivated by the observation that the
                  construction based on trapdoor functions lack
                  following two deficencies:
                  - trapdoor one-wayness doesn't exclude that f(x)
                    might be invertible if x is of special form.
                  - it can also not be ruled it (and in fact in most
                    cases is not the case!) that partial information
                    on the input is leaked.
                  They define a public key cryptosystem (PKC) as a
                  turing machine (TM) $\Pi$ that on input $k$ the security
                  parameter and a TM $MG$ the message generator
                  (sampler) provides descriptions of a TM E
                  (encryption) and D (decryption) such what $D(E(m)) =
                  m | \forall m \in MG(k)$. All TMs are probabilistic and
                  polynomial time (in input). Note it is essential for
                  encryption that the TM is probabilistic to meet the
                  security definitions! 

                  They provide two definitions for secure PKC (taking
                  only passive attackers into account!):
                  - polynomial security:
                    $ |P(A(E(m_1),aux)=1) - P(A(E(m_2),aux)=1)| < 1/p(k) ::
                       \forall polynomials p(k);
                       \forall MG(k); 
                       {E,D} <- \Pi(k,MG);
                       \forall A,F \in P/poly(k);
                       {m_1, m_2, aux} <- F(E,MG)$
                  - semantic security:
                    $ |P(A(E(m), 1^n)=f(m)) - P(A'(1^n)=f(m))| < 1/p(k) ::
                       \forall polynomials p(k);
                       \forall MG(k); 
                       \forall f; 
                       \forall A \in P/poly(k);
                       \exists A'  \in P/poly(k);
                       {E,D} <- \Pi(k,MG);
                       m <- MG(k)$
                     Note that for the uniform version one normally
                     adds an input (arbitrary computable) h(m) to A
                     and A' to model apriori knowledge. For
                     non-uniform however adding h() doesn't add
                     strength. see \cite{Goldre93}. 
                     Also note that f does not have to be computable,
                     not even recursive.
                  It can be shown, partially here, partially later
                  (\cite{Goldre93}) that these notions are equivalent
                  under non-uniform and uniform complexity definitions.

                  They provide and proof secure under above definition
                  following PKC: encrypt bit-by-bit bit $b_i$ with a
                  unapproximable trapdoor predicate (UTP) $B$ (ala
                  hardcore predicate) by selecting a random element
                  fulfilling $x_i$ so that $B(x_i) = b_i$. An example
                  system secure under the quadratic residuosity
                  assumption is as follows:          
                  $SK$ (trapdoor): prime $p_1,p_2$ of size $k$
                  $PK$: $n=p_1p_2$, $y$ a QNR with jacobisymbol 1.
                  $E$: foreach bit $b_i$ { $x_i \random \Z{n}^*; e_i := x_i^2 y^b_i$}
                  $D$: foreach encryption bit $e_i$ { $b_i := Q_n(e_i)$ }
                  },
	added-at	= {Thu Oct 14 15:31:49 1999},
	pages	= {270-299},
	volume	= 28
}

