  added-at =	 {Fri Jun  9 08:42:41 2000},
  annote =		 {This paper addresses security issues that arise in an ad-hoc
                  wireless network of mobile devices. The main difficulty are
                  power- and computation-constrained devices (Peanut-CPU). This
                  prevents usage of most asymmetric techniques. They address the
                  following issues:
                  - Availability. They present a battery power exhaustion
                    attack ("sleep deprivation torture attack"). Most mobile
                    devices are usually in sleep mode, so waking them up and
                    making them compute requires precious battery power.
                  - Authenticity. They state that a new problem in this
                    environment is the absence of an online server. The goal is
                    secure transient association, meaning that new devices can be
                    integrated securely in an environment. They propose the
                    "resurrecting duckling" security policy, which uses a
                    mechanism similar to the imprinting of birds after they hatch
                    the egg: the new-hatched bird recognizes the first moving
                    object it sees which makes a special sound as its
                    mother. So if we get a new device, we use physical contact to
                    perform key exchange (imprinting). (They also have process
                    called reverse metempsychosis to describe what happens after
                    death of the device).
                  - Integrity. Since signatures are too expensive, use shared
                    keys and MAC to achieve data integrity (and authenticity). 
