                  test with ${(g^y)}^{x/S}$).
                  For the first case one has to make sure that $g$ is
                  not 1 which is unlikely (1/q) for sufficiently large
                  order subgroups.
                  we might operate for efficiency reasons in a small
                  subgroup (note that $g$ can be precomputed/cached on the
                  server side! But also care has to be taken that no
                  other really small subgroups exist or the
                  performance advantage is gone (e.g you have to check
                  the order of received elements!)) though taking
                  \cite{OorWie96} into account we might also use small
